{
  "What is the primary function of the heart?": "",
  "To produce red blood cells": "",
  "To pump blood through the circulatory system, delivering oxygen and nutrients to tissues": "",
  "To exchange gases with the atmosphere": "",
  "To filter waste products from the blood": "",
  "The heart is a muscular pump with four chambers that keeps blood circulating. The right side pumps deoxygenated blood to the lungs (pulmonary circuit), and the left side pumps oxygenated blood to the body (systemic circuit). Filtering waste is the kidneys' job; producing RBCs is the bone marrow's job; gas exchange happens in the lungs.": "",
  "What are arteries?": "",
  "Tubes that carry lymph fluid": "",
  "Blood vessels that carry blood away from the heart": "",
  "The smallest vessels where gas exchange occurs": "",
  "Blood vessels that carry blood toward the heart": "",
  "Arteries carry blood AWAY from the heart (remember: A = Away). Most arteries carry oxygenated blood, except the pulmonary arteries, which carry deoxygenated blood from the right ventricle to the lungs. Arteries have thick, muscular, elastic walls to withstand high blood pressure generated by the heart's pumping action.": "",
  "What are veins?": "",
  "Vessels that connect arteries directly to arteries": "",
  "Vessels only found in the lungs": "",
  "Veins return blood to the heart. Most veins carry deoxygenated blood, except the pulmonary veins, which carry oxygenated blood from the lungs to the left atrium. Veins have thinner walls than arteries and contain one-way valves to prevent backflow, since blood pressure is much lower on the return trip.": "",
  "Where does gas and nutrient exchange between blood and body tissues occur?": "",
  "In veins — they are closest to tissues": "",
  "In arteries — they carry oxygenated blood": "",
  "In the heart chambers during contraction": "",
  "In capillaries — their walls are only one cell thick": "",
  "Capillaries are the smallest blood vessels (5-10 μm diameter) and the only ones where exchange occurs. Their walls are just one endothelial cell thick, creating the shortest diffusion distance for O₂, CO₂, glucose, and waste products to pass between blood and tissues. Arteries and veins have walls too thick for efficient diffusion.": "",
  "What is the function of red blood cells (erythrocytes)?": "",
  "To produce antibodies against foreign substances": "",
  "To fight infections and destroy pathogens": "",
  "To form blood clots at wound sites": "",
  "To transport oxygen from the lungs to body tissues using hemoglobin": "",
  "Red blood cells contain hemoglobin, an iron-containing protein that binds oxygen in the lungs and releases it in tissues. Mature mammalian RBCs lack a nucleus, maximizing space for hemoglobin. Fighting infections is the role of white blood cells (leukocytes); clotting is the role of platelets (thrombocytes); antibody production is the role of B lymphocytes specifically.": "",
  "What are the four chambers of the heart?": "",
  "Superior, inferior, anterior, and posterior": "",
  "Aorta, vena cava, pulmonary artery, and pulmonary vein": "",
  "Right atrium, right ventricle, left atrium, and left ventricle": "",
  "Tricuspid, mitral, aortic, and pulmonary": "",
  "The heart has four chambers: two upper atria (receive blood) and two lower ventricles (pump blood out). The right atrium receives deoxygenated blood from the body; the right ventricle pumps it to the lungs. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the lungs; the left ventricle pumps it to the body. The aorta, vena cava, etc. are blood vessels, not chambers; tricuspid and mitral are valves.": "",
  "What do the two numbers in a blood pressure reading represent?": "",
  "Heart rate over respiratory rate": "",
  "Oxygen level over carbon dioxide level": "",
  "Red blood cell count over white blood cell count": "",
  "Systolic (pressure during heart contraction) over diastolic (pressure during heart relaxation)": "",
  "Blood pressure is measured as systolic/diastolic in mmHg. Systolic (top number) is the pressure when the left ventricle contracts and pushes blood into the aorta. Diastolic (bottom number) is the pressure when the heart relaxes between beats. Normal blood pressure is approximately 120/80 mmHg. Hypertension (chronically high BP) damages arteries and increases risk of stroke and heart attack.": "",
  "Which type of blood cell fights infections?": "",
  "Platelets (thrombocytes)": "",
  "White blood cells (leukocytes)": "",
  "Red blood cells (erythrocytes)": "",
  "Plasma cells only": "",
  "White blood cells (leukocytes) are the immune system's defenders. There are several types: neutrophils (most abundant, first responders to bacteria), lymphocytes (B cells make antibodies, T cells kill infected cells), monocytes (become macrophages that engulf debris), eosinophils (target parasites), and basophils (involved in allergic responses). Red blood cells carry oxygen and platelets help with clotting.": "",
  "What is the function of platelets (thrombocytes)?": "",
  "To help form blood clots at wound sites to stop bleeding": "",
  "To produce antibodies against infections": "",
  "To regulate blood pressure": "",
  "To carry oxygen throughout the body": "",
  "Platelets are cell fragments (from megakaryocytes in bone marrow) that initiate blood clotting. When a vessel is damaged, platelets stick to exposed collagen, form a temporary plug, and release chemicals that activate the coagulation cascade — ultimately producing fibrin threads that reinforce the clot. Low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) causes excessive bleeding; excessively high counts can cause dangerous clots.": "",
  "What is the difference between the pulmonary circuit and the systemic circuit?": "",
  "The pulmonary circuit only carries oxygen; the systemic circuit only carries carbon dioxide": "",
  "They are two names for the same pathway": "",
  "The pulmonary circuit uses arteries; the systemic circuit uses veins only": "",
  "The pulmonary circuit carries blood between the heart and lungs; the systemic circuit carries blood between the heart and the rest of the body": "",
  "The circulatory system has two circuits. The pulmonary circuit: right ventricle → pulmonary arteries → lungs (gas exchange) → pulmonary veins → left atrium. The systemic circuit: left ventricle → aorta → body tissues (delivers O₂, picks up CO₂) → vena cava → right atrium. Both circuits use arteries and veins. The left ventricle is thicker because the systemic circuit is much longer and requires more pumping force.": "",
  "What is plasma?": "",
  "Another name for red blood cells that transport oxygen through the circulatory system": "",
  "The membrane surrounding blood vessels that forms the walls of arteries and veins": "",
  "The liquid component of blood (~55% of blood volume) composed of water, proteins, electrolytes, and dissolved substances": "",
  "The clotting factor that forms fibrin threads at wound sites to stop hemorrhaging": "",
  "Plasma is the straw-colored liquid matrix of blood. It is about 90% water and carries dissolved proteins (albumin, fibrinogen, immunoglobulins), electrolytes (Na⁺, K⁺, Ca²⁺), glucose, hormones, waste products, and gases. When blood is centrifuged, plasma separates as the top layer, with a thin buffy coat (WBCs/platelets) in the middle and packed red blood cells at the bottom.": "",
  "What is hemoglobin?": "",
  "A plasma protein involved in blood clotting": "",
  "A hormone that regulates heart rate": "",
  "A white blood cell that fights bacterial infections": "",
  "An iron-containing protein in red blood cells that binds and transports oxygen": "",
  "Hemoglobin (Hb) is a protein with four subunits, each containing an iron-containing heme group that can reversibly bind one O₂ molecule (total: 4 O₂ per hemoglobin). In the lungs, high O₂ concentration causes hemoglobin to load oxygen (oxyhemoglobin — bright red). In tissues, low O₂ and high CO₂ cause hemoglobin to release oxygen (deoxyhemoglobin — dark red). Each RBC contains ~270 million hemoglobin molecules. Low hemoglobin = anemia.": "",
  "What is atherosclerosis?": "",
  "The buildup of fatty plaques (cholesterol, calcium, and inflammatory cells) inside artery walls, narrowing the vessel lumen": "",
  "The weakening and bulging of a vein wall, forming a venous aneurysm that may rupture": "",
  "A condition where blood cannot clot properly, leading to prolonged bleeding after injury": "",
  "An infection of the heart valves caused by bacteria entering the bloodstream from wounds": "",
  "Atherosclerosis is a progressive disease where plaques of cholesterol, fat, calcium, and inflammatory cells accumulate in artery walls, narrowing and stiffening them. This reduces blood flow and can lead to angina (chest pain). If a plaque ruptures and a clot forms on it, the artery can become completely blocked — causing a heart attack (coronary artery) or stroke (cerebral artery). Risk factors: high LDL cholesterol, smoking, hypertension, diabetes, and sedentary lifestyle.": "",
  "What is the sinoatrial (SA) node?": "",
  "A cluster of specialized cells in the right atrium that generates electrical impulses to initiate each heartbeat — the heart's natural pacemaker": "",
  "A blood vessel that supplies the heart muscle with oxygen": "",
  "A chamber of the heart that pumps blood to the lungs": "",
  "A valve that separates the left atrium from the left ventricle": "",
  "The SA node is the heart's natural pacemaker, located in the wall of the right atrium. It spontaneously generates electrical impulses at 60-100 bpm, which spread through the atria (triggering atrial contraction), then travel to the AV node, Bundle of His, and Purkinje fibers to trigger ventricular contraction. If the SA node fails, artificial pacemakers can be implanted to deliver timed electrical stimuli.": "",
  "What is the ABO blood group system?": "",
  "The pathway blood takes through the four heart chambers": "",
  "A type of immune response against bacteria": "",
  "A system that measures how many red blood cells are in the blood": "",
  "A classification system based on the presence or absence of A and B antigens on red blood cell surfaces, determining blood type compatibility": "",
  "The ABO system classifies blood based on surface antigens: Type A has A antigens (and anti-B antibodies in plasma), Type B has B antigens (anti-A antibodies), Type AB has both antigens (no antibodies — universal recipient), and Type O has neither antigen (both antibodies — universal donor). Transfusion of incompatible blood causes agglutination (clumping) and hemolysis when antibodies attack foreign antigens. The Rh factor (+ or −) adds another antigen to consider.": "",
  "What is cardiac output?": "",
  "The number of red blood cells produced per day": "",
  "The pressure of blood against artery walls": "",
  "The volume of blood pumped by the heart per minute, calculated as heart rate × stroke volume": "",
  "The electrical signal generated by the SA node": "",
  "Cardiac output (CO) = heart rate (HR) × stroke volume (SV). At rest: ~70 bpm × ~70 mL = ~5 L/min — meaning the heart pumps the entire blood volume approximately once per minute. During exercise, both HR and SV increase, raising CO to 20-25 L/min in trained athletes. Cardiac output is a key measure of heart function; heart failure occurs when CO is insufficient to meet the body's oxygen demands.": "",
  "What is a hematocrit?": "",
  "The speed at which blood clots form": "",
  "The percentage of blood volume occupied by red blood cells, normally about 42-52% in males and 37-47% in females": "",
  "The ratio of arteries to veins in the body": "",
  "The total number of white blood cells per liter of blood": "",
  "Hematocrit is determined by centrifuging a blood sample: packed RBCs settle at the bottom, and their percentage of total blood volume is the hematocrit. A low hematocrit indicates anemia (too few RBCs or too little hemoglobin); a high hematocrit (polycythemia) makes blood more viscous and increases clot risk. Athletes training at high altitude naturally increase their hematocrit because low oxygen stimulates erythropoietin (EPO) production from the kidneys.": "",
  "What is the Rh factor in blood typing?": "",
  "A type of white blood cell involved in immune defense against foreign pathogens": "",
  "A protein (antigen D) on the surface of red blood cells — Rh+ means it is present, Rh− means it is absent": "",
  "A clotting factor in plasma that converts fibrinogen into fibrin during coagulation": "",
  "The ratio of hemoglobin to plasma in blood, which determines oxygen-carrying efficiency": "",
  "The Rh factor (named after the Rhesus monkey where it was first discovered) is the D antigen on RBC surfaces. About 85% of people are Rh+ (have the antigen). The Rh factor is critical in pregnancy: if an Rh− mother carries an Rh+ fetus, her immune system may produce anti-Rh antibodies that could attack the fetal RBCs in subsequent pregnancies (hemolytic disease of the newborn). RhoGAM injection prevents this sensitization.": "",
  "What is vasoconstriction?": "",
  "The widening of blood vessels that decreases blood pressure": "",
  "The destruction of blood vessel walls by immune cells": "",
  "The formation of blood clots inside vessels": "",
  "The narrowing of blood vessels due to contraction of smooth muscle in the vessel walls, which increases blood pressure": "",
  "Vasoconstriction is the narrowing of blood vessels when smooth muscle in the vessel walls contracts. This increases peripheral resistance and raises blood pressure. The opposite — vasodilation — widens vessels, decreasing resistance and lowering blood pressure. The sympathetic nervous system triggers vasoconstriction during stress or cold (redirecting blood to vital organs). Many blood pressure medications work by promoting vasodilation.": "",
  "What is a myocardial infarction?": "",
  "An irregular heartbeat caused by SA node malfunction": "",
  "A heart attack — death of heart muscle tissue caused by blockage of a coronary artery cutting off blood supply": "",
  "A congenital hole between the two atria": "",
  "Inflammation of the heart valves": "",
  "A myocardial infarction (MI) occurs when a coronary artery becomes blocked — usually by a ruptured atherosclerotic plaque and subsequent blood clot. The heart muscle downstream of the blockage is deprived of oxygen and begins to die within minutes. Symptoms include chest pain, shortness of breath, and pain radiating to the left arm or jaw. Emergency treatment includes clot-dissolving drugs (thrombolytics), angioplasty with stent placement, or coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG).": "",
  "A patient arrives at the ER with chest pain. An ECG shows the SA node is not firing properly, so a cardiologist recommends an artificial pacemaker. A medical student asks: 'Why can't the heart just beat without the SA node?' The cardiologist explains:": "",
  "The SA node is the heart's natural pacemaker — without it, backup pacemakers fire too slowly (40-60 bpm or less) to maintain adequate circulation": "",
  "The SA node is only needed during exercise, not at rest": "",
  "Without the SA node, the heart stops completely and cannot beat at all": "",
  "The SA node produces the blood that fuels cardiac contraction": "",
  "The SA node normally fires at 60-100 bpm. If it fails, backup pacemakers can take over: the AV node (~40-60 bpm) or ventricular Purkinje fibers (~20-40 bpm). The heart doesn't stop completely, but these slower rates may be insufficient to maintain blood pressure and organ perfusion — causing dizziness, fainting, or even death. Artificial pacemakers deliver electrical impulses at 60+ bpm to replace the SA node's function, ensuring adequate cardiac output.": "",
  "A doctor explains the path of blood through the heart to a nursing student. Starting from deoxygenated blood returning from the body, the correct sequence is: vena cava → right atrium → right ventricle → pulmonary arteries → lungs → pulmonary veins → left atrium → left ventricle → aorta. The student asks: 'Why do pulmonary arteries carry deoxygenated blood if arteries are supposed to carry oxygenated blood?'": "",
  "The pulmonary arteries carry oxygenated blood, so the textbook description of the pathway is wrong": "",
  "All arteries carry deoxygenated blood throughout the body, since oxygenation only occurs in veins": "",
  "Arteries are defined by direction (away from the heart), not oxygen content — pulmonary arteries carry deoxygenated blood away from the right ventricle to the lungs": "",
  "Pulmonary arteries are actually veins that were mislabeled by early anatomists who studied cadavers": "",
  "This is the most commonly tested distinction in cardiovascular biology. Arteries = carry blood AWAY from the heart. Veins = carry blood TOWARD the heart. Most arteries carry oxygenated blood and most veins carry deoxygenated blood — but the pulmonary vessels are exceptions. Pulmonary arteries carry deoxygenated blood from the right ventricle to the lungs; pulmonary veins carry oxygenated blood from the lungs to the left atrium. The classification is about direction, not gas content.": "",
  "A marathon runner's muscles need constant oxygen delivery. During the race, her hemoglobin oxygen saturation drops from 98% to 75% in the capillaries surrounding her quadriceps. A sports medicine student asks why hemoglobin releases more oxygen at the muscles than at the lungs. The answer involves:": "",
  "The muscles actively pump oxygen out of red blood cells": "",
  "Hemoglobin is destroyed by the acid in muscle tissue": "",
  "Hemoglobin only works in the lungs and is inactive elsewhere": "",
  "The Bohr effect — in active muscles, low O₂, high CO₂, low pH, and high temperature cause hemoglobin to release oxygen more readily": "",
  "The Bohr effect explains how hemoglobin's oxygen affinity changes with local conditions. In active muscles: high CO₂ (from cellular respiration), low pH (lactic acid), and elevated temperature shift the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve to the RIGHT — meaning hemoglobin releases O₂ more easily exactly where it's needed most. In the lungs, the opposite conditions (high O₂, low CO₂, higher pH) promote O₂ loading. This automatic adjustment ensures efficient O₂ delivery without any conscious control.": "",
  "A patient with a coronary artery 80% blocked by plaque is diagnosed with severe atherosclerosis. Their cardiologist explains that if the plaque ruptures, a blood clot could form on top of it. A scared patient asks: 'What happens if the clot completely blocks my coronary artery?'": "",
  "Only the lungs would be affected": "",
  "The body will immediately reroute blood through other arteries with no damage": "",
  "The blockage would dissolve on its own within hours": "",
  "A myocardial infarction (heart attack) — the heart muscle downstream of the blockage dies from oxygen deprivation within minutes": "",
  "Coronary arteries supply the heart muscle itself with oxygen. Atherosclerotic plaques narrow these arteries over decades. When a plaque ruptures, the body's clotting mechanisms activate at the site, potentially creating a thrombus that completely occludes the vessel. Without blood flow, the heart muscle (myocardium) begins dying — this is a myocardial infarction. Time is critical: 'time is muscle.' Emergency treatments include thrombolytics (clot-dissolving drugs), balloon angioplasty with stent placement, or coronary artery bypass grafting.": "",
  "A blood test reveals a patient has type AB+ blood. During a discussion, a medical student claims this patient can receive blood from any donor but wants to understand why. The immunological explanation is:": "",
  "AB+ blood has extra-powerful white blood cells that accept all transfusions": "",
  "AB+ red blood cells have A, B, and Rh antigens — so the immune system won't attack any donated blood with these antigens, and the patient has no anti-A, anti-B, or anti-Rh antibodies": "",
  "AB+ blood has no antigens, making it invisible to the immune system": "",
  "AB+ patients don't have an immune system, so they can't reject blood": "",
  "Blood type compatibility depends on antigens (on RBC surfaces) and antibodies (in plasma). Type AB+ has ALL antigens (A, B, and Rh), so the immune system recognizes all of them as 'self' and produces NONE of the corresponding antibodies. Without anti-A, anti-B, or anti-Rh antibodies, the body cannot attack any donated blood type. Conversely, Type O− is the universal donor because its RBCs have no antigens to trigger a recipient's antibodies.": "",
  "A pregnant woman who is Rh-negative (Rh−) is carrying her second Rh-positive (Rh+) baby. During her first pregnancy, small amounts of fetal blood mixed with hers during delivery. Now her doctor is concerned. What complication could affect this second baby, and how is it prevented?": "",
  "No risk exists because Rh incompatibility only affects the mother's own red blood cells and health": "",
  "The mother will develop Rh+ blood permanently after being exposed to fetal Rh+ antigens in the blood": "",
  "Hemolytic disease of the newborn — the mother's anti-Rh antibodies can cross the placenta and destroy the fetus's Rh+ red blood cells; prevented by RhoGAM injection": "",
  "The second fetus will automatically become Rh-negative to match the mother's blood type genetically": "",
  "During the first Rh+ pregnancy, fetal RBCs leaking into the Rh− mother's blood at delivery trigger her immune system to produce anti-Rh IgG antibodies (sensitization). In a subsequent Rh+ pregnancy, these small IgG antibodies cross the placenta and attack the fetal Rh+ red blood cells, causing hemolytic disease (erythroblastosis fetalis) — severe anemia and jaundice in the newborn. Prevention: RhoGAM (anti-D immunoglobulin) given at 28 weeks and within 72 hours of delivery destroys fetal RBCs before the mother's immune system can respond.": "",
  "A pathologist compares cross-sections of an artery, a vein, and a capillary under a microscope. The artery has thick muscular/elastic walls and no valves. The vein has thinner walls with visible valves. The capillary is just one cell thick. A student asks: 'Why is the artery wall so much thicker than the vein wall?'": "",
  "Arteries receive blood directly from the heart at high pressure — thick muscular and elastic walls are needed to withstand and regulate that pressure": "",
  "Arteries need thick walls because they carry more blood volume than veins": "",
  "Thick artery walls prevent oxygen from escaping before reaching tissues": "",
  "Artery walls are thick because they also produce blood cells": "",
  "When the left ventricle contracts, it generates ~120 mmHg of pressure that blood vessels must withstand. Arteries have thick walls with smooth muscle (for vasoconstriction/dilation) and elastic fibers (to stretch and recoil with each pulse). By the time blood reaches veins, pressure has dropped to ~5-15 mmHg, so thick walls aren't needed. Instead, veins have valves to prevent backflow and rely on skeletal muscle contractions to push blood back to the heart against gravity.": "",
  "An anemic patient with hemoglobin of 7 g/dL (normal: 12-16) reports constant fatigue, shortness of breath during mild exercise, and pale skin. A medical student asks why low hemoglobin causes these specific symptoms. The doctor explains:": "",
  "Low hemoglobin causes blood to clot too slowly, leading to internal bleeding throughout all major organs": "",
  "Low hemoglobin increases blood pressure to dangerous levels by thickening the blood's viscosity overall": "",
  "Less hemoglobin = less oxygen-carrying capacity → tissues are oxygen-starved → the heart and lungs work harder to compensate, causing fatigue and shortness of breath; pallor results from less oxyhemoglobin in skin capillaries": "",
  "Anemia only affects the digestive system, causing nutrient malabsorption and chronic gastrointestinal problems": "",
  "Hemoglobin is the oxygen transporter. At 7 g/dL (about half normal), the blood can only carry about half the normal oxygen load. Tissues become hypoxic, and the body compensates by increasing heart rate (tachycardia) and respiratory rate (tachypnea) — explaining the fatigue and shortness of breath. Pale skin and nail beds occur because deoxyhemoglobin (dark red) predominates over oxyhemoglobin (bright red) in skin capillaries. The body can also increase erythropoietin production to stimulate new RBC production.": "",
  "During intense exercise, a runner's heart rate increases from 70 to 170 bpm and her blood vessels to skeletal muscles dilate while those to the digestive system constrict. Which division of the nervous system orchestrates this coordinated response, and why does blood get redirected?": "",
  "The parasympathetic nervous system ('rest and digest') — it increases heart rate during stress": "",
  "The sympathetic nervous system ('fight or flight') — it redirects blood from non-essential organs to active muscles by selective vasoconstriction and vasodilation": "",
  "The somatic nervous system — voluntary control of heart rate and blood vessels": "",
  "The enteric nervous system — it controls all exercise responses": "",
  "The sympathetic nervous system coordinates the 'fight or flight' response: heart rate and contractility increase (via norepinephrine on the SA node), blood vessels to skeletal muscles dilate (to deliver more O₂), and vessels to digestive organs constrict (to redirect blood where it's needed). The adrenal medulla also releases epinephrine, amplifying these effects. The parasympathetic system does the opposite ('rest and digest'): slows heart rate and promotes digestion. This is why exercising right after eating can cause cramps — blood flow competition.": "",
  "A patient with varicose veins has visible, bulging, twisted veins in their legs. The vascular surgeon explains the underlying cause: the one-way valves in these veins have weakened. A student asks: 'If arteries don't have valves, why do veins need them?' The surgeon explains the physics:": "",
  "Venous blood pressure is very low (~5-15 mmHg), so without valves, gravity would pull blood backward and pool it in the legs — arteries don't need valves because high pressure (120 mmHg) keeps blood flowing forward": "",
  "Arteries have internal valves that are just too small to see under standard histological examination": "",
  "Veins are made of weaker material that needs valves for structural support against external compression": "",
  "Valves in veins produce the energy needed to push blood upward against gravity through muscular contraction": "",
  "By the time blood reaches leg veins, the heart's pumping pressure has dissipated to just 5-15 mmHg — not enough to overcome gravity on its own. One-way venous valves allow blood to flow upward toward the heart but slam shut to prevent backflow. The 'skeletal muscle pump' (leg muscles squeezing veins during walking) pushes blood upward between valves. When valves weaken, blood pools, veins distend, and varicose veins form. Risk factors: prolonged standing, pregnancy, obesity, and genetics.": ""
}